  "base_commit": "d8a12ad6be3f57ca49eeba394a49151500f1e18b",
  "pr_number": 1835,
  "issue_number": 2022,
  "issue_title": "Bug: Financial data reset can leave family-scoped records behind",
  "issue_body": "## Problem\n\nThe financial data reset path and reset-status endpoint should describe and operate on the same family-scoped data surface. If the reset job only clears a narrow subset of records, family-owned financial, import, reference, provider, or attachment data can remain after reset, and reset status can report completion against a different surface than the destructive job actually deletes.\n\n## Expected behavior\n\n- Reset behavior is centralized in one service with an explicit family-scoped deletion surface.\n- Reset status uses the same scope as the reset job.\n- Provider cleanup only touches associations that are explicitly safe to reset.\n- Reset work is idempotent and does not affect another family.\n- API docs describe the reset-status response shape accurately.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- Replace the inline reset-job deletion list with a reusable family financial reset service.\n- Include accounts, entries, transactions, transfers, holdings, balances, rules, budgets, taxonomies, imports, exports, statements, provider items, syncs, and related attachments where applicable.\n- Keep destructive queries scoped through the current family or family-owned IDs.\n- Update reset-status docs and regression coverage for idempotency and two-family isolation.\n\nRelated implementation: #1835\n",
  "merged_at": "2026-05-30T22:21:34.000Z",
